    "body": "### Problem\n\nOn windows systems\n\nvim.fn.fnamemodify can result in a path mixing both slashes and backslashes.\n\nReproducible on `v0.10.4` with `--clean`\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim --clean\n`:lua vim.print(vim.fn.fnamemodify([[C:/Users]], ':p'))`\n\nActual Results:\n`C:/Users\\`\n\nThis behavior chains with vim.fs.normalize:\n\n`:lua vim.print(vim.fn.fnamemodify(vim.fs.normalize([[C:\\Users\\]]), ':p'))`\n\nSame result as above.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nConsistent application of the appropriate path separator.  Given the clear distinction in behavior between fn.fnamemodify and fs.normalize regarding the preference of one separator vs the other, I don't claim to know the right behavior.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nUnknown\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11 Pro v23H2\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nPowershell 5.1.22621.4391\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nEmpty\n\n### Installation\n\nnvim-win64.msi",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
